Description: CVE-2026-55200 - Additional boundary checks for packet length
 libssh2 through 1.11.1 contains an out-of-bounds write vulnerability in
 ssh2_transport_read() where the packet_length field read from the network
 was not bounds-checked at every read site. An attacker can send a crafted
 SSH packet with an oversized packet_length to corrupt heap memory and
 potentially achieve remote code execution (CWE-680).
 .
 Upstream commit 97acf3df (PR #2052) adds the missing
 "p->packet_length > LIBSSH2_PACKET_MAXPAYLOAD" check at the
 REQUIRES_FULL_PACKET / encrypt-then-MAC code path that was introduced in
 libssh2 versions newer than 1.9.0.
 .
 The 1.9.0 code base shipped in Debian bullseye does NOT contain that
 newer code path: src/transport.c has only one read site for
 p->packet_length (via _libssh2_ntohu32(block) at line 440) and that site
 already enforces both the lower bound (< 1 -> LIBSSH2_ERROR_DECRYPT) and
 the upper bound (> LIBSSH2_PACKET_MAXPAYLOAD ->
 LIBSSH2_ERROR_OUT_OF_BOUNDARY) at lines 441-446. The vulnerable third
 read site that the upstream fix protects does not exist in 1.9.0.
 .
 To match the upstream fix's defence-in-depth posture this backport adds
 a redundant safety check immediately before p->packet_length is consumed
 by the padding_length / total_num arithmetic. The check is functionally
 redundant given the existing guard at 444-446, but ensures any future
 refactor that moves the early guard cannot silently re-introduce the
 OOB-write primitive.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/libssh2/libssh2/commit/97acf3dfda80c91c3a8c9f2372546301d4a1a7a8
Bug: https://github.com/libssh2/libssh2/pull/2052
Bug-Debian: https://bugs.debian.org/1140401
Author: Will Cosgrove <will@panic.com>
Last-Update: 2026-06-24
---
--- a/src/transport.c
+++ b/src/transport.c
@@ -445,6 +445,12 @@
                 return LIBSSH2_ERROR_OUT_OF_BOUNDARY;
             }

+            /* CVE-2026-55200: additional defence-in-depth boundary check
+               on packet_length before it is used in arithmetic below. */
+            if(p->packet_length > LIBSSH2_PACKET_MAXPAYLOAD) {
+                return LIBSSH2_ERROR_OUT_OF_BOUNDARY;
+            }
+
             p->padding_length = block[4];
             if(p->padding_length > p->packet_length - 1) {
                 return LIBSSH2_ERROR_DECRYPT;
Description: CVE-2026-55199 - SSH_MSG_EXT_INFO DoS - not applicable on bullseye
 Upstream commit 17626857 (PR #1864, released in libssh2 1.11.1) fixes a
 pre-authentication DoS in the SSH_MSG_EXT_INFO handler in src/packet.c:
 unchecked _libssh2_get_string() return values let a malicious server set
 nr_extensions to a huge value and spin the client in a CPU-bound loop.
 .
 Debian bullseye ships libssh2 1.9.0-2+deb11u1. The SSH_MSG_EXT_INFO
 handler (and nr_extensions parsing) was introduced upstream in libssh2
 1.11.0 and is absent from 1.9.0: src/packet.c has no case SSH_MSG_EXT_INFO
 and no nr_extensions variable. Debian's bullseye patches (CVE-2020-22218,
 CVE-2019-17498, etc.) do not backport EXT_INFO support either.
 .
 The vulnerable code path does not exist; applying the upstream +4/-2 hunk
 fails with no matching context. This hook documents not-affected status.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/libssh2/libssh2/commit/17626857d20b3c9a1addfa45979dadcee1cd84a4
Bug: https://github.com/libssh2/libssh2/pull/1864
Bug-Debian: https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2026-55199
Author: TristanInSec <tristan.mtn@gmail.com>
Last-Update: 2026-07-22
