@@ -0,0 +1,55 @@
+# CVE-2026-55199 — Not Affected on Debian Bullseye libssh2 1.9.0
+
+| Field | Value |
+|-------|-------|
+| **CVE** | CVE-2026-55199 |
+| **Component** | libssh2 `SSH_MSG_EXT_INFO` handler (`src/packet.c`) |
+| **Package** | libssh2 1.9.0-2+deb11u1 |
+| **Assessment** | **Not affected** — vulnerable code not present |
+| **VEX justification** | `vulnerable_code_not_present` |
+| **CWE** | CWE-400 (Uncontrolled Resource Consumption) |
+| **Upstream fix** | commit `17626857d20b3c9a1addfa45979dadcee1cd84a4` (PR #1864) |
+
+---
+
+## Summary
+
+CVE-2026-55199 is a pre-authentication denial-of-service in libssh2 through
+1.11.1. A malicious SSH server can send a crafted `SSH_MSG_EXT_INFO` with a
+huge `nr_extensions` count; because `_libssh2_get_string()` return values
+were ignored, the client can spin in a CPU-bound loop for a long time.
+
+The upstream fix checks `_libssh2_get_string()` and breaks the loop on
+parse failure.
+
+---
+
+## Why Debian Bullseye is not affected
+
+Bullseye ships **libssh2 1.9.0**. The `SSH_MSG_EXT_INFO` handler was added
+upstream in **libssh2 1.11.0**. In the bullseye source tree:
+
+- `src/packet.c` has **no** `case SSH_MSG_EXT_INFO`
+- There is **no** `nr_extensions` parsing loop
+- Debian `debian/patches/` does not introduce EXT_INFO support
+
+Tag checks:
+
+| Version | `SSH_MSG_EXT_INFO` in `src/packet.c` |
+|---------|--------------------------------------|
+| 1.9.0 (bullseye) | absent |
+| 1.10.0 (bookworm) | absent |
+| 1.11.0+ | present (vulnerable until 1.11.1 fix) |
+
+The upstream hunk cannot apply and is unnecessary: the vulnerable path is
+absent from this package version.
+
+**CVE-2026-55199 is not-affected on libssh2 1.9.0-2+deb11u1.**
+
+---
+
